{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848154140,"sessionID":"ses_28733c4faffe3d66rps1PQCQ3M","part":{"id":"prt_d78cc5ac1001M9hQPmby4xr2BW","messageID":"msg_d78cc5004001Y6ERX44NME2P0o","sessionID":"ses_28733c4faffe3d66rps1PQCQ3M","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_7aae7c6f12bd4c21b457014c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/tasks.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/tasks.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心 Tasks\n2: \n3: **Module:** pkg/router  \n4: **Language:** Go  \n5: **Size:** M  \n6: **Stage:** ST-3 (Implementation)\n7: \n8: ---\n9: \n10: ## Phase 1: Core Infrastructure\n11: \n12: - [ ] **1.1** Create `pkg/router/config.go` — Config struct with defaults (listen `:8080`, backend timeout `30s`, idle timeout `60s`, health check `10s`)\n13: - [ ] **1.2** Create `pkg/router/server.go` — Router struct with Start/Shutdown methods\n14: - [ ] **1.3** Create `pkg/router/backend.go` — Backend pool management (add/remove/update endpoints)\n15: - [ ] **1.4** Create `pkg/router/proxy.go` — Reverse proxy implementation with httputil\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## Phase 2: Kubernetes Informers\n20: \n21: - [ ] **2.1** Create `pkg/router/informer.go` — Setup AgentRuntime informer with namespace filtering\n22: - [ ] **2.2** Create `pkg/router/informer.go` — Setup CodeInterpreter informer with namespace filtering\n23: - [ ] **2.3** Implement `addAgentRuntime()` handler — Add endpoint when AgentRuntime phase=Running\n24: - [ ] **2.4** Implement `updateAgentRuntime()` handler — Update endpoint on status change\n25: - [ ] **2.5** Implement `deleteAgentRuntime()` handler — Remove endpoint on CR deletion\n26: - [ ] **2.6** Implement `addCodeInterpreter()` handler — Add endpoint when CodeInterpreter phase=Running\n27: - [ ] **2.7** Implement `updateCodeInterpreter()` handler — Update endpoint on status change\n28: - [ ] **2.8** Implement `deleteCodeInterpreter()` handler — Remove endpoint on CR deletion\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## Phase 3: Routing Logic\n33: \n34: - [ ] **3.1** Create `pkg/router/route.go` — Path prefix matching (e.g., `/agent/` → backend)\n35: - [ ] **3.2** Create `pkg/router/route.go` — Header-based routing (X-Backend, Content-Type)\n36: - [ ] **3.3** Implement 404 response for unmatched paths\n37: - [ ] **3.4** Implement query parameter preservation in routing\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## Phase 4: Health Checking\n42: \n43: - [ ] **4.1** Create `pkg/router/health.go` — Periodic health check scheduler\n44: - [ ] **4.2** Implement health check request with 5s timeout\n45: - [ ] **4.3** Implement unhealthy backend removal (3 consecutive failures)\n46: - [ ] **4.4** Implement backend recovery (mark healthy on success)\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## Phase 5: Connection Pooling\n51: \n52: - [ ] **5.1** Configure httputil.ReverseProxy with Transport for keep-alive\n53: - [ ] **5.2** Implement max connections per backend limit (default 100)\n54: - [ ] **5.3** Implement idle connection cleanup (idleTimeout)\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ## Phase 6: Middleware\n59: \n60: - [ ] **6.1** Create `pkg/router/ratelimit.go` — Token bucket rate limiting (enable/disable)\n61: - [ ] **6.2** Create `pkg/router/auth.go` — Bearer token validation middleware\n62: - [ ] **6.3** Create `pkg/router/logging.go` — Request/response logging middleware\n63: \n64: ---\n65: \n66: ## Phase 7: Metrics\n67: \n68: - [ ] **7.1** Implement `router_request_duration_seconds` histogram\n69: - [ ] **7.2** Implement `router_backend_requests_total` counter\n70: - [ ] **7.3** Implement `router_backend_healthy` gauge\n71: - [ ] **7.4** Implement `router_errors_total` counter\n72: \n73: ---\n74: \n75: ## Phase 8: Verification\n76: \n77: - [ ] **8.1** `go build ./pkg/router/...` — successful compilation\n78: - [ ] **8.2** `go test ./pkg/router/... -v` — all unit tests pass\n79: - [ ] **8.3** Integration test: Router starts, discovers CRs, routes requests\n80: \n81: ---\n82: \n83: ## Dependencies\n84: \n85: - `k8s.io/client-go/informers` — Kubernetes informers\n86: - `k8s.io/client-go/listers` — CR listers\n87: - `github.com/prometheus/client_golang/prometheus` — Metrics\n88: \n89: ---\n90: \n91: ## References\n92: \n93: - Delta Spec: `changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md`\n\n(End of file - total 93 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心 Tasks\n\n**Module:** pkg/router  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Stage:** ST-3 (Implementation)\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1: Core Infrastructure\n\n- [ ] **1.1** Create `pkg/router/config.go` — Config struct with defaults (listen `:8080`, backend timeout `30s`, idle timeout `60s`, health check `10s`)\n- [ ] **1.2** Create `pkg/router/server.go` — Router struct with Start/Shutdown methods\n- [ ] **1.3** Create `pkg/router/backend.go` — Backend pool management (add/remove/update endpoints)\n- [ ] **1.4** Create `pkg/router/proxy.go` — Reverse proxy implementation with httputil\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2: Kubernetes Informers\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/tasks.md","time":{"start":1775848154120,"end":1775848154139}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775848154143,"sessionID":"ses_28733c4faffe3d66rps1PQCQ3M","part":{"id":"prt_d78cc5f6f001H2jVb15sUnKPmA","messageID":"msg_d78cc5004001Y6ERX44NME2P0o","sessionID":"ses_28733c4faffe3d66rps1PQCQ3M","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_c6e0691751934a27be762727","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n6: \n7: ## Base Specifications\n8: \n9: - **AR**: AR-009\n10: - **Module**: `pkg/router`\n11: - **Language**: Go\n12: - **Size**: M\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Background\n17: \n18: The router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services dynamically discovered from AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## Requirement: Router Configuration\n23: \n24: ### Scenario: Router loads configuration with defaults\n25: \n26: **GIVEN** a Router instance is created with no explicit configuration\n27: **WHEN** the router starts\n28: **THEN** it SHOULD use default values: listen address `:8080`, backend timeout `30s`, idle timeout `60s`, health check interval `10s`\n29: \n30: ### Scenario: Router loads custom configuration\n31: \n32: **GIVEN** a Router instance is created with custom configuration\n33: **WHEN** the configuration specifies `listenAddress: \":9090\"`, `backendTimeout: \"60s\"`, `rateLimitEnabled: true`, `rateLimitRPS: 50`\n34: **THEN** the router SHOULD listen on port 9090, use 60s backend timeout, and enable rate limiting at 50 RPS\n35: \n36: ### Scenario: Router watches specific namespaces\n37: \n38: **GIVEN** a Router configured with `watchNamespaces: [\"ns1\", \"ns2\"]`\n39: **WHEN** the router starts its informers\n40: **THEN** it SHOULD only watch AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs in namespaces \"ns1\" and \"ns2\"\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## Requirement: HTTP Server Lifecycle\n45: \n46: ### Scenario: Router starts HTTP server\n47: \n48: **GIVEN** a configured Router instance\n49: **WHEN** `Start()` is called\n50: **THEN** an HTTP server SHOULD start listening on the configured address\n51: **AND** the server SHOULD be ready to accept incoming requests\n52: \n53: ### Scenario: Router graceful shutdown\n54: \n55: **GIVEN** a running Router with active connections\n56: **WHEN** `Shutdown()` is called with a context\n57: **THEN** the server SHOULD stop accepting new connections\n58: **AND** it SHOULD wait for in-flight requests to complete within the context timeout\n59: **AND** it SHOULD close all idle connections\n60: \n61: ### Scenario: Router handles server startup error\n62: \n63: **GIVEN** a Router configured with an invalid address (e.g., unsupported port)\n64: **WHEN** `Start()` is called\n65: **THEN** it SHOULD return an error indicating the address is invalid or port is not accessible\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: ## Requirement: Endpoint Discovery from AgentRuntime CR\n70: \n71: ### Scenario: Router discovers new AgentRuntime endpoint\n72: \n73: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime informer running\n74: **WHEN** a new AgentRuntime CR is created with `status.endpoint: \"http://10.0.0.1:8080\"` and `status.phase: Running`\n75: **THEN** the router SHOULD add the endpoint to its backend pool\n76: **AND** the endpoint SHOULD be available for routing\n77: \n78: ### Scenario: Router removes deleted AgentRuntime endpoint\n79: \n80: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime endpoint in its backend pool\n81: **WHEN** the corresponding AgentRuntime CR is deleted\n82: **THEN** the router SHOULD remove the endpoint from the backend pool\n83: **AND** no new requests SHOULD be routed to that endpoint\n84: \n85: ### Scenario: Router updates AgentRuntime endpoint on status change\n86: \n87: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime endpoint in its backend pool\n88: **WHEN** the AgentRuntime CR status is updated with a new endpoint address\n89: **THEN** the router SHOULD update the backend pool with the new endpoint\n90: **AND** existing connections to the old endpoint SHOULD be closed\n91: \n92: ### Scenario: Router ignores non-running AgentRuntime\n93: \n94: **GIVEN** a Router with an AgentRuntime informer\n95: **WHEN** an AgentRuntime CR is created with `status.phase: Pending`\n96: **THEN** the router SHOULD NOT add the endpoint to the backend pool\n97: \n98: ---\n99: \n100: ## Requirement: Endpoint Discovery from CodeInterpreter CR\n101: \n102: ### Scenario: Router discovers new CodeInterpreter endpoint\n103: \n104: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter informer running\n105: **WHEN** a new CodeInterpreter CR is created with `status.endpoint: \"http://10.0.0.2:8080\"` and `status.phase: Running`\n106: **THEN** the router SHOULD add the endpoint to its backend pool\n107: \n108: ### Scenario: Router removes deleted CodeInterpreter endpoint\n109: \n110: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter endpoint in its backend pool\n111: **WHEN** the corresponding CodeInterpreter CR is deleted\n112: **THEN** the router SHOULD remove the endpoint from the backend pool\n113: \n114: ### Scenario: Router updates CodeInterpreter endpoint on status change\n115: \n116: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter endpoint in its backend pool\n117: **WHEN** the CodeInterpreter CR status is updated with a new endpoint address\n118: **THEN** the router SHOULD update the backend pool with the new endpoint\n119: \n120: ### Scenario: Router ignores non-running CodeInterpreter\n121: \n122: **GIVEN** a Router with a CodeInterpreter informer\n123: **WHEN** a CodeInterpreter CR is created with `status.phase: Failed`\n124: **THEN** the router SHOULD NOT add the endpoint to the backend pool\n125: \n126: ---\n127: \n128: ## Requirement: Path-Based Routing\n129: \n130: ### Scenario: Router routes request by path prefix\n131: \n132: **GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://backend-1:8080\" registered for path prefix `/agent/`\n133: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/agent/session-123`\n134: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend-1:8080/session-123`\n135: \n136: ### Scenario: Router routes request to code interpreter path\n137: \n138: **GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://ci-1:8080\" registered for path `/code/`\n139: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/code/execute`\n140: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://ci-1:8080/execute`\n141: \n142: ### Scenario: Router returns 404 for unmatched path\n143: \n144: **GIVEN** a router with configured routes\n145: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/unknown/path`\n146: **THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 404 response\n147: \n148: ### Scenario: Router handles path with query parameters\n149: \n150: **GIVEN** a backend pool containing endpoint \"http://backend:8080\" registered for path `/api/`\n151: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with path `/api/data?param=value`\n152: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend:8080/data?param=value`\n153: \n154: ---\n155: \n156: ## Requirement: Header-Based Routing\n157: \n158: ### Scenario: Router routes request by custom header\n159: \n160: **GIVEN** a router configured with header-based routing rule: header `X-Backend` maps to corresponding backend\n161: **AND** a backend pool with endpoint \"http://backend-a:8080\" for header value \"backend-a\"\n162: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `X-Backend: backend-a`\n163: **THEN** the request SHOULD be proxied to `http://backend-a:8080`\n164: \n165: ### Scenario: Router routes request by content-type header\n166: \n167: **GIVEN** a router configured with header routing for `Content-Type`\n168: **AND** a backend pool with endpoint for JSON requests\n169: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `Content-Type: application/json`\n170: **THEN** the request SHOULD be routed to the appropriate backend\n171: \n172: ### Scenario: Router falls back to default when header not matched\n173: \n174: **GIVEN** a router configured with header-based routing and a default backend\n175: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received with header `X-Custom: unknown-value`\n176: **AND** no backend is configured for \"unknown-value\"\n177: **THEN** the request SHOULD be routed to the default backend\n178: \n179: ---\n180: \n181: ## Requirement: Health Checking\n182: \n183: ### Scenario: Router performs periodic health checks\n184: \n185: **GIVEN** a backend pool with endpoints\n186: **WHEN** the health check interval (default 10s) elapses\n187: **THEN** the router SHOULD send health check requests to each backend\n188: **AND** mark backends as healthy or unhealthy based on the response\n189: \n190: ### Scenario: Router removes unhealthy backend from pool\n191: \n192: **GIVEN** a backend pool with a healthy endpoint\n193: **WHEN** the endpoint fails health checks for 3 consecutive attempts\n194: **THEN** the router SHOULD mark the backend as unhealthy\n195: **AND** stop routing requests to that backend\n196: \n197: ### Scenario: Router adds recovered backend back to pool\n198: \n199: **GIVEN** a backend pool with an unhealthy endpoint\n200: **WHEN** the endpoint passes a health check\n201: **THEN** the router SHOULD mark the backend as healthy\n202: **AND** resume routing requests to that backend\n203: \n204: ### Scenario: Health check timeout\n205: \n206: **GIVEN** a backend endpoint that does not respond\n207: **WHEN** a health check request times out (default 5s)\n208: **THEN** the backend SHOULD be marked as unhealthy\n209: \n210: ---\n211: \n212: ## Requirement: Connection Pooling\n213: \n214: ### Scenario: Router reuses connections to backends\n215: \n216: **GIVEN** a router with connection pooling enabled\n217: **WHEN** multiple requests are routed to the same backend\n218: **THEN** the router SHOULD reuse existing connections via HTTP keep-alive\n219: **AND** not create a new connection for each request\n220: \n221: ### Scenario: Router limits connections per backend\n222: \n223: **GIVEN** a router configured with `maxConnsPerBackend: 100`\n224: **WHEN** more than 100 concurrent connections exist to a backend\n225: **THEN** the router SHOULD queue additional connection requests\n226: **OR** return an error indicating the backend is overloaded\n227: \n228: ### Scenario: Router closes idle connections\n229: \n230: **GIVEN** a router with `idleTimeout: 60s`\n231: **WHEN** a connection to a backend has been idle for 60 seconds\n232: **THEN** the router SHOULD close the idle connection\n233: \n234: ---\n235: \n236: ## Requirement: Rate Limiting\n237: \n238: ### Scenario: Rate limiting restricts requests per client\n239: \n240: **GIVEN** a router with rate limiting enabled (`rateLimitRPS: 10`)\n241: **WHEN** a client sends 15 requests per second\n242: **THEN** the router SHOULD allow 10 requests through\n243: **AND** return HTTP 429 for the remaining 5 requests\n244: \n245: ### Scenario: Rate limiting uses token bucket algorithm\n246: \n247: **GIVEN** a router with rate limiting enabled\n248: **WHEN** requests arrive at varying rates\n249: **THEN** the router SHOULD use token bucket algorithm for smooth rate limiting\n250: **AND** allow burst traffic up to the bucket size\n251: \n252: ### Scenario: Rate limiting is disabled by default\n253: \n254: **GIVEN** a router with default configuration\n255: **WHEN** the router starts without explicit rate limit settings\n256: **THEN** rate limiting SHOULD NOT be active\n257: **AND** all requests SHOULD be processed normally\n258: \n259: ---\n260: \n261: ## Requirement: Authentication Middleware\n262: \n263: ### Scenario: Router validates authentication token\n264: \n265: **GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n266: **WHEN** a request arrives with valid `Authorization: Bearer <token>`\n267: **THEN** the request SHOULD be allowed through\n268: \n269: ### Scenario: Router rejects unauthenticated request\n270: \n271: **GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n272: **WHEN** a request arrives without `Authorization` header\n273: **THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 401 response\n274: \n275: ### Scenario: Router rejects invalid token\n276: \n277: **GIVEN** a router with authentication enabled\n278: **WHEN** a request arrives with invalid `Authorization: Bearer <invalid-token>`\n279: **THEN** the router SHOULD return HTTP 401 response\n280: \n281: ### Scenario: Authentication is disabled by default\n282: \n283: **GIVEN** a router with default configuration\n284: **WHEN** the router starts without explicit auth settings\n285: **AND** a request arrives without authorization\n286: **THEN** the request SHOULD be allowed through\n287: \n288: ---\n289: \n290: ## Requirement: Metrics\n291: \n292: ### Scenario: Router exposes request latency metric\n293: \n294: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n295: **WHEN** a request is proxied to a backend\n296: **THEN** a Prometheus histogram `router_request_duration_seconds` SHOULD be recorded\n297: \n298: ### Scenario: Router exposes backend request count metric\n299: \n300: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n301: **WHEN** requests are proxied to backends\n302: **THEN** a Prometheus counter `router_backend_requests_total` SHOULD be incremented per backend\n303: \n304: ### Scenario: Router exposes backend health status metric\n305: \n306: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n307: **WHEN** backend health status changes\n308: **THEN** a Prometheus gauge `router_backend_healthy` SHOULD reflect the status (1=healthy, 0=unhealthy)\n309: \n310: ### Scenario: Router exposes error rate metric\n311: \n312: **GIVEN** a router with metrics enabled\n313: **WHEN** a proxied request fails (backend error or timeout)\n314: **THEN** a Prometheus counter `router_errors_total` SHOULD be incremented\n315: \n316: ---\n317: \n318: ## Requirement: Request Logging\n319: \n320: ### Scenario: Router logs incoming requests\n321: \n322: **GIVEN** a router with logging middleware active\n323: **WHEN** an HTTP request is received\n324: **THEN** the log SHOULD contain: method, path, client IP, timestamp\n325: \n326: ### Scenario: Router logs proxied response status\n327: \n328: **GIVEN** a router with logging middleware active\n329: **WHEN** a proxied request completes\n330: **THEN** the log SHOULD contain: status code, response time, backend URL\n331: \n332: ---\n333: \n334: ## Acceptance Criteria\n335: \n336: - [ ] Router loads configuration with proper defaults\n337: - [ ] Router starts and listens on configured address\n338: - [ ] Router gracefully shuts down with active connections\n339: - [ ] Endpoints are discovered from AgentRuntime CRs with Running phase\n340: - [ ] Endpoints are removed when AgentRuntime CR is deleted\n341: - [ ] Endpoints are discovered from CodeInterpreter CRs with Running phase\n342: - [ ] Endpoints are removed when CodeInterpreter CR is deleted\n343: - [ ] Requests are routed based on path prefix\n344: - [ ] Requests are routed based on custom headers\n345: - [ ] 404 is returned for unmatched paths\n346: - [ ] Health checks run at configured intervals\n347: - [ ] Unhealthy backends are removed from routing pool\n348: - [ ] Healthy backends are restored after recovery\n349: - [ ] Connection pooling reuses HTTP connections\n350: - [ ] Connection limits per backend are enforced\n351: - [ ] Rate limiting restricts requests when enabled\n352: - [ ] Rate limiting allows requests when disabled\n353: - [ ] Authentication validates bearer tokens\n354: - [ ] Unauthenticated requests are rejected when auth enabled\n355: - [ ] Metrics are exported for Prometheus scraping\n356: - [ ] Request logs contain method, path, status, duration\n357: - [ ] Graceful shutdown completes within timeout\n\n(End of file - total 357 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-009 — Router HTTP 反向代理核心\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing the HTTP reverse proxy core in `pkg/router`.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-009\n- **Module**: `pkg/router`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: M\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe router module is responsible for routing HTTP requests to backend Sandbox services dynamically discovered from AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter CRs. This delta implements the core HTTP reverse proxy functionality.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-009/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775848154123,"end":1775848154141}}}}
